'''Matthew David "Matt" Bischoff''' (born May 21, 1987 in [[Decatur, Indiana]]) is a [[professional baseball]] player who is currently a member of the [[Seattle Mariners]] [[minor league baseball|minor league]] organization. Bischoff, a [[pitcher]], bats and throws [[right-handed]].<ref name="brmmatthewbis">{{cite web|title=Matthew Bischoff Minor League Statistics & History|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/player.cgi?id=bischo001mat|work=Baseball-Reference|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=25 September 2010}}</ref> He stands at {{convert|6|ft|0|in|m}} and weighs {{convert|190|lb|kg}}.<ref name=brmmatthewbis /> Bischoff attended [[New Haven High School (Indiana)|New Haven High School]] where he set a school career record in [[win (baseball)|wins]] and [[strikeouts]]. He then enrolled at [[Purdue University]] where he played baseball for four years (2007<U+2013>2010). He was the [[Big Ten]] [[Freshman]] of the Year in 2007. Bischoff holds the career and single season strikeouts record for Purdue's baseball team. From Purdue, he was drafted by the Seattle Mariners during the [[2010 Major League Baseball Draft]]. He made his professional baseball debut at the [[Minor league baseball#Rookie|rookie-level]] level with the [[Pulaski Mariners]] that year.

==Amateur career==
===High school===
Bischoff attended [[New Haven High School (Indiana)|New Haven High School]], where he was a four-year [[letterman]].<ref name=mattbiscollege /> During his [[freshman]] season, he compiled a [[win<U+2013>loss record|record]] of 3<U+2013>2 with a 3.20 [[earned run average]] (ERA), nine [[save (baseball)|saves]], and 63 [[strikeouts]].<ref name=mattbiscollege /> In his [[sophomore]] campaign, Bischoff went 9<U+2013>1 with a 1.20 ERA, and 120 strikeouts.<ref name=mattbiscollege /> His strikeout total broke a school record.<ref name=mattbiscollege /> He was named to the all-conference team after the season.<ref name=mattbiscollege /> Bischoff went 11<U+2013>2 with a 0.70 ERA, and 137 strikeouts during his [[junior (education)|junior]] season.<ref name=mattbiscollege /> He broke the school's strikeout record, which he set the season before.<ref name=mattbiscollege /> He was a first team all-conference, first team all-area, and first team all-state member that season.<ref name=mattbiscollege /> In his [[senior (education)|senior]] year, Bischoff went 12<U+2013>3 with 133 strikeouts.<ref name=mattbiscollege /> After the season, the ''[[Fort Wayne News-Sentinel]]'' named Bischoff as the male athlete of the year.<ref name=mattbiscollege /> He holds the school record in career [[win (baseball)|wins]] (35), and strikeouts (453).<ref name=mattbiscollege /> Bischoff also played [[tennis]], and [[basketball]] while in high school.<ref name=mattbiscollege /> For all four of his years on the school's baseball team, his father, Dave Bischoff, was his [[coach (baseball)|coach]].<ref name=mattbiscollege /> 

===College===
Bischoff attended [[Purdue University]] from 2007 to 2010. In his freshman season, he compiled a record of 3<U+2013>2 with a 2.85 ERA, one [[complete game]], one [[shutout]], two saves, and 61 strikeouts in 14 games, six [[starting pitcher|starts]].<ref name="mattbiscube">{{cite web|title=Matt Bischoff|url=http://www.thebaseballcube.com/players/B/Matt-Bischoff.shtml#Awards|work=TheBaseballCube.com|publisher=The Baseball Cube|accessdate=25 September 2010}}</ref> That season, he was named the [[Big Ten]] Freshman of the Year.<ref name="mattbiscollege">{{cite web|title=Player Bio: Matt Bischoff|url=http://www.purduesports.com/sports/m-basebl/mtt/bischoff_matt00.html|work=Purdue University Athletics Department|publisher=CBS Interactive|accessdate=25 September 2010}}</ref> Bischoff was also named a ''[[Collegiate Baseball Newspaper]]'' Freshman [[All-American]], and a second team All-Big Ten selection.<ref name=mattbiscollege /> During his sophomore season, Bischoff went 6<U+2013>3 with a 3.96 ERA, and 55 strikeouts in 14 games, all starts.<ref name=mattbiscube /> He was a first team All-Big Ten selection that year.<ref name=mattbiscollege /> After the season, Bischoff was drafted by the [[New York Mets]] in the 47{{sup|nd}} round of the [[2008 Major League Baseball Draft]].<ref>{{cite web|title=47th Round of the 2008 MLB June Amateur Draft|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/draft/?year_ID=2008&draft_round=47&draft_type=junreg&query_type=year_round|work=Baseball-Reference|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=25 September 2010}}</ref> 

In his junior campaign, Bischoff compiled a 4<U+2013>5 record with a 5.54 ERA, three complete games, and 80 strikeouts in 14 games, all starts.<ref name=mattbiscube /> He was a third team All-Big Ten selection that season.<ref name=mattbiscollege /> In his final season at Purdue, Bischoff compiled a 10<U+2013>2 record with a 3.22 ERA, two complete games, and 95 strikeouts in 13 games, all starts.<ref name=mattbiscube /> Bischoff was selected in the 20{{sup|th}} round of the [[2010 Major League Baseball Draft]] by the [[Seattle Mariners]].<ref>{{cite web|title=20th Round of the 2010 MLB June Amateur Draft|url=http://www.baseball-reference.com/draft/?year_ID=2010&draft_round=20&draft_type=junreg&query_type=year_round|work=Baseball-Reference|publisher=Sports Reference, LLC|accessdate=25 September 2010}}</ref> Bischoff currently holds the Purdue career record for strikeouts with 291.<ref name="mattbisdrafted">{{cite web|title=Seattle Drafts Matt Bischoff: Right-hander tabbed in the 20th round by the Mariners|url=http://www.purduesports.com/sports/m-basebl/spec-rel/060810aab.html|publisher=CBS Interactive|accessdate=25 September 2010|date=8 June 2010}}</ref> His 2010 strikeouts total is also a school single-season record. He was also the first player in school history to win All-Big Ten honors all four years.<ref>{{cite web|last=McCall|first=Mike|title=Mariners begin Day 2 with two prep picks|date=8 June 2010|url=http://seattle.mariners.mlb.com/news/print.jsp?ymd=20100608&content_id=10955446&vkey=news_sea&fext=.jsp&c_id=sea|work=MLB.com|publisher=Major League Baseball|accessdate=25 September 2010}}</ref>

==Professional career==
After signing with the Seattle Mariners in 2010, Bischoff was assigned to the [[Minor league baseball#Rookie|rookie-level]] [[Pulaski Mariners]]. ''[[Baseball America]]'' described Bischoff as doing an "excellent job of competing with average [[Glossary of baseball (S)#Stuff|stuff]]".<ref>{{cite web|last=Stone|first=Larry|title=Second-day MLB draft running thread: M's take high school SS Marcus Littlewood in second round, highly rated HS pitcher in 3rd|url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/thehotstoneleague/2012059084_ms_take_high_school_ss_marcus.html|work=The Seattle Times|publisher=The Seattle Times Company|accessdate=25 September 2010|date=8 June 2010}}</ref> That season, he compiled a 4<U+2013>4 record with a 3.30 ERA, five saves, and 45 strikeouts in 17 games, all in [[relief pitcher|relief]].<ref name=brmmatthewbis /> Bischoff was promoted to the [[Minor league baseball#Class A|Class-A]] [[Clinton LumberKings]] during their [[post-season]] run in the [[Midwest League]] playoffs.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lezotte|first=Dave|title=Mailloux, Bischoff Join Kings for Playoffs|url=http://saltlake.bees.milb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20100908&content_id=14436612&vkey=news_t500&fext=.jsp&sid=t500|work=MiLB.com|publisher=Minor League Baseball|accessdate=25 September 2010|date=8 September 2010}}</ref>

